[1] Cholera - Myanmar
Date: Thu, 6 Oct 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Democratic Voice of Burma [edited]
<http://www.dvb.no/english/news.php?id=3150>

4 people died from cholera
--------------------------
At least 4 people at Pwintphyu Township, Magwe Division in central Burma,
died from cholera, which broke out after the inundations caused by heavy
rains during September 2004.
The flood waters brought sewage into homes, and many people suffered from
cholera at Yeboke Gyi Village. As a result, a 44-year-old, a 35-year-old,
and 2 30-year-olds died from the outbreak.
The floods also destroyed the paddy-crops twice, causing farmers acute
difficulties, and they are finding it hard to replant the new batch of
paddies. They could not afford to replant the rice due to the cost and are
waiting the chance to grow cold-season crops.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
